<br>
It makes sense that the next expansion would focus on high lvl content and added planes, since Luclin was directed towards mid to low lvl encounters with some high end zones, but no planes (that I know of).<br>
<br>
With regards to EQ2, I don't really understand the reference to Microsoft that was made earlier.  Perhaps you could explain it a little more.  Microsoft does't compete with itself.  Sure it releases upgrades (tho some would challenge that term, since the product seems to get worse with each upgrade...sorry, soap box), but Office XP replaces Office 2000 and so on.  After a period of time, support for the older product is dropped (ie Windows 95).  I don't really see how that model applies to what we're talking about here.  Of course, when Microsoft starts charging for subscription based service, where upgrades to their products are available as long as your subscription is active; then maybe there would be similarity...right now, I just don't see your point, I guess.  /shrug<br>
<br>
Anyway, EQ2 is probably inevitable...but I don't see it coexisting with EQ any more than Nintendo coexists with SNES coexists with N64 coexists with the Gamecube.   Again, this is apples and oranges, but in principle, if enough people flock to EQ2, then EQ is history.  If not, then VI is history and we'll all have to find something else to do.../shiver, just kidding.  <br>
<br>
I don't know if I would be willing to part with several high lvl chars for a new gaming experience (not that I have SEVERAL, but who knows what I'll have by then...hehe).  Considering the time invested in each character, it would be very difficult to just drop EQ and start again...sure the &quot;fresh start&quot; would be nice; but that novelty would only last for a short time.<br>
<br>
